<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900911-0098</DOCNO><DOCID>900911-0098.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Shanghai Eases Its Curbs   On Foreign Bank Branches</HL><DATE>09/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18</SO><CO>   FREST FORGN</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   HONG KONG -- In addition to new regulations for its Pudongindustrial project, Shanghai announced rules allowing foreignbanks to operate bank branches and other financialinstitutions in the city proper.   Foreign bankers said that, while the scope of business maybe too restrictive to make operating a branch profitable, thetough rules won't deter them from trying to gain a toehold inShanghai, an industrial and commercial center and formerregional financial center. Until now, Beijing has allowedforeign banks to open branches only in the country's fivespecial economic zones.</LP><TEXT>   Four foreign banks -- Hongkong andamp; Shanghai Banking Corp.,Standard Chartered Bank, Bank of East Asia andOverseas-Chinese Banking Corp. -- already have Shanghaibranches, which they established before the Communisttakeover in 1949. This number will grow as the municipalgovernment is expected to approve the first batch of newapplicants soon.</TEXT></DOC>